description:
Belle Soliva brought in several ifil, Intsia bijuga, seedlings (Fabaceae) being killed by a stem boring lep.

To date, more than half of I. bijuga seedlings in the Guam DOA Forestry Nursery have been killed by this pest.

Specimens sent to Dr. Marc Epstein for species determination.

Following examination of specimens by Dr. Epstein and his colleague, Dr. Todd Gilligan, it was concluded that the ifit stem borer is a species in the genus Cryptophlebia:
"I dissected male and female specimens from the material you sent me and both match Cryptophlebia ombrodelta from Todd and my TortAI work. The molecular data matched specimens in BOLD for this species or Cryptophlebia illepida.
The find on Ifit, Intsia bijuga, appears to be a new host record, at least according to TortAI." [extracted from email from M. Epstein to A. Moore, June 2, 2017]

C. ombrodelta has been previously reported on Guam, but C. illepida is known only from Hawaii.

description: This observation and images belong to Donald Buden, College of Micronesia, Pohnpei, FSM. This small paper wasp is Ropalidia marginata. It is very common in the Mariana Islands, where it is locally referred to as one of two species of "boonie bees". This observation indicates a range extension into Mejit Island. Previously recorded in the Marshall Isands on Kwajalein Atoll (Sugarman 1972). References Swezey, OH, 1942. Wasps of Guam. In Insects of Guam I.: Listed under the synonym Icaria marginata Sugerman, Bernard B. 1972. “Insects and Other Arthropods from Kwajalein Atoll (Marshall Islands).” http://scholarspace.manoa.hawaii.edu/handle/10125/11013. GBIF

Stinging ants were first detected by Augustin Garong in Wanyaan, Gagil Island, Yap. Francis Liyeg, Joe Tutu, Andrew Yinifel of the Yap Invasive Species Program and John Pekalpal visited the site and collected specimens on August 22, 2017. On August 25, 2017 Dr. Murukesan Krishnapillai, College of Micronesia, Colonia, Yap, emailed me images of ants for identification. I could not identify the ants from the images and requested specimens. Dr. Krishnapillai dropped off dried ant specimens with the Guam Customs and Quarantine Authority while transiting through the Guam International Airport on August 27. Microscopic examination indicates that these specimens are little fire ant (LFA), Wasmannia auropunctata. Lee Roy Sablan and Ian Iriarte examined specimens under the microscope and agree with this diagnosis. This appears to be the first record for LFA in Yap and the other Federated States of Micronesia. An initial estimate of the area covered by LFA on August 29, 2017 is 155,482 square feet (14,445 square metres).

description: These mites were collected from an outbreak of mites in an office in the Agriculture and Life Sciences Building at the University of Guam. Body length = 0.4 mm This mite is probably Glycyphagus domesticus, the furniture mite. I have found no previous occurrence records for this mite on Guam. The outbreak was probably the result of high humidity due to inadequate air conditioning. On Aug 21, RH was 76% and temperature was 73 deg. F. in the infested office. The optimal relative humidity for development of these mites is 70-90%; under 65% humidity the mites desiccate Wagner 2018.
